Countries with cases but no ongoing transmission
---
Germany (case report). 5 Jul 2016. (conf.) One case ex Viet Nam; A 47-year-old female German traveler returning from a 6-day business trip from Viet Nam presented at our clinic on 17 Jun [2016] in Berlin, 6 days after arrival, with a history of fatigue (day 2 till day 4 after arrival), persisting mild diarrhea (starting day 2 after arrival), and a macular non-confluent symmetrical rash starting on the trunk and arms (starting day 6 after arrival). The diarrhea disappeared on day 9. A moderate bilateral pain localized in both ankle and wrist had started on day 7 and responded partially to Ibuprofen. Neither the past medical history nor physical examination revealed any further findings. Full recovery on day 10 after onset of symptoms.

Full blood count showed a moderate leucopenia (2/nl). Rapid tests for Dengue IgM and IgG were negative. Further lab results were normal. An additional blood sample was sent to the WHO Collaborating Centre for Arbovirus at the Bernhard Nocht-Institute for Tropical Medicine. Dengue and CHIKV were negative by serology on 30 Jun [2016]. Zika virus results returned positive (IgM IIFT and PCR). Pregnancy was excluded, and the patient was counseled for precautions in regards of contraceptive measures and blood donations.

Our patient's itinerary involved Berlin, Frankfurt, Ho Chi Minh City (Saigon) and Hanoi without any further stops or travel history in or outside Germany. She recognized mosquito bites only in Hanoi. To our knowledge, this is the 1st traveler returning from Viet Nam to Europe with a ZIKV-infection during the current ZIKV epidemic in the Americas. Two confirmed cases of ZIKV-infections in returning travelers in Viet Nam were reported so far, one in Korea and one in Israel. No further reported cases until now. The presence of ZIKV was reported 1963 in Viet Nam (Trans R Soc Trop Med Hyg 1963 Sep; 57:364-71). This case again illustrates the role of returning travelers as potential disease sentinels, that Zika is likely circulating more widely than officially reported, and the inadequacy of information about Zika virus circulation in Asia.

(Information submitted by Joerg Sasse, MD, DTMH (London), Gerhard Boecken, MD, MSc IHT (London), Health Services, German Foreign Office Berlin, Germany <gerhard.boecken@diplo.de>)

[ProMED thanks Drs. Sasse and Boeken for providing this case report.]

