[3] Zika and Olympic games
Date: Mon 27 Jun 2016
Source: Travel Medicine & Infectious Disease [edited]
http://www.travelmedicinejournal.com/article/S1477-8939(16)30073-4/fulltext


Marcia C. Castro. Zika virus and the 2016 Olympic Games - Evidence-based projections derived from dengue do not support cancellation.

Abstract
From 5-21 Aug [2016] more than 10 000 athletes from about 200 countries will gather in Rio de Janeiro (RJ), Brazil, for the 2016 Summer Olympics. Thousands of domestic and international tourists are expected to attend the games. From 7-8 Sep [2016], RJ will also host the Paralympic Games. Concern has been raised around the public health consequences of the Games, given the Zika virus (ZIKV) situation in Brazil. Calls for canceling, transferring, or postponing the games have been made, including an open letter (https://rioolympicslater.org/) sent to the World Health Organization (WHO).

[Conclusion]
To suggest that the Olympics should be moved from Brazil, canceled or postponed because of ZIKV is not based on disease knowledge and on scientific assessment. Evidence shows that the epidemiological conditions in RJ in August and September 2016 will not pose a major risk for ZIKV transmission. Yet, the WHO recommendation for pregnant women not to travel to areas with active ZIKV transmission must be followed, given the consequences of congenital ZIKV syndrome. Considering the current available knowledge, if ZIKV does spread much faster post-Olympics, it will be a result of lack of preparedness and inefficiencies in health systems and surveillance policies of individual countries.

--
Communicated by:
Roland Hubner
Superior Health Council
Brussels
